equivalent undergraduate</td> <td>68 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Status as a commuter campus</td> <td>67 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Average high school GPA among college freshmen</td> <td>64 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Percent of undergraduate students age 25 and over</td> <td>62 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Admissions selectivity, per <em>Barron&apos;s Profiles of American Colleges</em></td> <td>54 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Percent of undergraduates who are enrolled part-time</td> <td>51 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Percent of degrees awarded in Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics</td> <td>30 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Historically Black College or University</td> <td>27 points</td> </tr> </tbody> </table> <h2>Average Annual Change</h2> <p>The average annual improvement rates reported in the table to the right of the Historical Trends line chart, were calculated using the formula below:</p> <p class="formula"><span class="numerator">G<sub>2</sub> &mdash; G<sub>1</sub></span><span class="division_line">⎯⎯⎯⎯⎯⎯⎯</span><span class="denominator">Y<sub>2</sub> &mdash; Y<sub>1</sub> </span></p> <p>where <em>G</em><sub>2</sub> is the most recent year&apos;s graduation rate, <em>G</em><sub>1</sub> is the graduation rate of the earliest year in the selected time frame, <em>Y</em><sub>2</sub> is the most recent year, and <em>Y</em><sub>1</sub> is the earliest year in the selected time frame.</p> <h2>Projected Trends</h2> <p>Two methodologies are presented for projecting graduation rates for CSU campuses: "Peer Benchmarking Methodology" and "Linear Model".</p> <h3>Peer Benchmarking Methodology</h3> <p>This methodology calculates a central projection along with related upper and lower bounds. The central projection is generated by first calculating the average 2008 graduation rate for the selected campus&apos; top five peers. This value is presented as the 2008 value for the three "Peer Benchmarking Methodology" projections. (Note that the "top five peers" can include the campus itself if it is among the top five performing institutions among its CRO peers.) For the central projection, subsequent values incrementally increase (or decrease) the 2008 value by cumulatively adding the average rate of change observed over the past 5 years for the top five peer institutions. Upper and lower projections are also based on the 2008 average graduation rate for the top five peers. These values are incremented by cumulatively adding the average rate of change observed over the past 5 years for the top five peer institutions plus the standard deviation of this average change (for the upper bound) or minus the standard deviation of this average change (for the lower bound).</p> <h3>Linear Model (Linear Programming Model)</h3> <p>The linear programming (or linear optimization model) generates potential campus graduation rate targets by working backwards from specific pre-determined constraints. This includes specific System-wide graduation rate targets (35% or 40% for 4-year graduation rate goals, and 65% or 70% for 6-year graduation rate goals), as well as closing URM and Pell achievement gaps at every campus. It provides an alternate approach for goal-setting compared to trend and/or benchmarking approaches. Campus graduation rates are broken down by Pell and URM status, resulting in 92 different graduation rate groups that comprise the whole System (23 campuses X URM/Non-URM groups X Pell Eligible/Non-Eligible groups).</p> <p>Campus rates are derived based on optimizing an objective function by varying graduation rates across the groups that minimizes the variance in the percentage point change in graduation rates across all groups. Using this as the objective, all groups should improve by similar rates. This will necessarily diverge with the additional constraints of meeting all of the Graduation Initiative objectives, including closing achievement gaps. Rates are based on the latest cohort for which final Pell grant awards are available, which corresponds to the Fall 2014 cohort.</p> <p>Models were run for target rates (4-year/6-year first-time, full-time freshmen), using the following System targets.</p> <table id="model_methods" class="table table-striped"> <thead> <tr> <th>Goal</th> <th>Cohort Group</th> <th>Current Rate</th> <th>System Target 1</th> <th>System Target 2</th> </tr> </thead> <tbody> <tr> <td>4-Year Graduation Rate Goal (2021 Cohort)</td> <td>First-time, Full-Time Freshmen</td> <td>19.1%</td> <td>35.0%</td> <td>40.0%</td> </tr> <tr> <td>6-Year Graduation Rate Goal (2019 Cohort)</td> <td>First-time, Full-Time Freshmen</td> <td>57.0%</td> <td>65.0%</td> <td>75.0%</td> </tr> </tbody> </table> <p>The model assumes a target System-wide graduation rate along with some other constraints. The individual rate for any subgroup (by campus/Pell/URM must be greater than or equal to the most recent available rate (2009 cohort for 6 year and 2011 cohort for 4 year). Additional constraints are imposed within the models that bounds the percentage point change for any single campus. Targets 1 and 2 use an upper bound of a 20 percentage point increase for campus 4yr rates. Target 3 uses a 25 percentage point upper bound and 10 percentage point lower bound for growth for each campus. The models also enforce a Pell and URM achievement gap that is less than or equal to zero.</p>', 'creeser', '2016-09-13 16:50:08', '2016-09-13 16:50:08', NULL),
(169, 2, 'sankey/applying', 'Published description...', 'sankey/applying', 1, 1, '<h1>Applying This Data</h1> <p><strong>The "What Paths Do They Follow?" page is intended to provide a clearer picture of the relative rates of migration into and out of the selected major as well as where they go or from where they came.</strong></p> <p>This chart is based only on the students&apos; major as declared at entry and at graduation. It does not show intervening discipline changes for students who made multiple migrations during their academic career. This chart also does not include students who are still enrolled, who transferred out of the university, or who did not graduate.</p> <p>This data may be of interest in its own right, but is likely most useful as a point of consideration when interpreting other data in this report or from other sources. For example, if, when reviewing the data in the &ldquo;Who Are My Students?&rdquo; page, you see that there are fewer juniors and seniors in the selected major than you expected, you might explore this chart to see if transferring to other majors is a contributing factor.</p> <p>Here are a few suggestions for applying this data:</p> <ul> <li>For majors that predominantly attract many students from other majors, consider reviewing where those students originate and discuss with other faculty and departments how well prepared they may be for the selected major when they arrive.</li> <li>For majors that predominantly send many students to other majors, consider surveying and discussing with departing students their reasons for changing majors.</li> </ul>', 'chris', '2016-09-21 16:59:55', '2016-09-21 16:59:55', NULL),
(170, 2, 'sankey/method', 'Published description...', 'sankey/method', 1, 1, '<h1>Methodology</h1> <p>The chart displayed shows major migration patterns for all first time, full time students who graduated in 2013, 2014, or 2015 with an undergraduate degree, by college and major. The majors represent the major chosen at entry and the major in which the student graduates. The data presented in these charts are taken from data originally sent by each campus&apos; Institutional Research department to the Chancellor&apos;s Office via the Enrollment Reporting System Student and Enrollment Reporting System Degree files (ERSS and ERSD, respectively). College and major alignments were also obtained from the Institutional Research department for the campuses shown.</p> <p>Specific variables included in the analysis from the degree file (ERSD) are as follows: degree level code, discipline code, major degree code, grad year, and grad term. The following variables were included from the ERSS files: cohort/year of entry, major degree code at entry, discipline code at entry, degree objective code at entry and major code. In addition, college and major were adding in for each major degree code using the alignment files received from campuses or created at the Chancellor&apos;s Office.</p> <p>A data set was created for the subset of ERSD variables used where grad year was in 2013, 2014, or 2015 and degree level was an undergraduate degree value (2, 3, or 4). A data set was also created with the subset of ERSS variables used that only included students who were first time full time (12 units or more) freshmen and where the cohort/matriculation year was greater than or equal to 1999.</p> <p>The ERSD and ERSS data sets that were created were then merged together and several enrolled and graduation variables were retained based on the major degree code: college at matriculation, major code at matriculation, major name at matriculation, college at graduation, major code at graduation, and major name at graduation for students at the campuses shown. Finally, a count variable was created to obtain the number of students graduating in each major code by major at matriculation using the following grouping order: major degree code at graduation, college at graduation, major name at graduation, college at matriculation major name at matriculation and major code at matriculation.</p>', 'chris', '2016-09-21 17:00:03', '2016-09-21 17:00:03', NULL),
(171, 2, 'sankey/explanations', 'Published description...', 'sankey/explanations', 1, 1, '<h1>Chart Explanation</h1> <h2>What data am I looking at?</h2> <p>The data used to create this chart were&nbsp;taken from data originally sent by each campus&apos; Institutional Research department to the Chancellor&apos;s Office in order to meet the campus&apos; Federal and State data reporting requirements. The Major Migration chart shows the relative proportion of students migrating into or out of the selected major (or remaining within the selected major). This chart is based only on the major as declared at entry and at graduation for students who began at the selected campus as first-time full-time freshmen. It does not show intervening major changes for students who made multiple migrations during their academic career. This chart also does not include students who are still enrolled, who transferred out of the university, or who did not graduate.</p> <h2>How do I interact with this page?</h2> <p>Use the menus at the top to select a campus, college, and major. Use the radio buttons at the top right to select different perspectives. You can choose to view just migrations into the selected major (the default view), migrations out of the selected major, or both at the same time. You can hover over a specific path to see the percent of student migrating from or to a specific major. You can also select the Data Tables tab to see the actual counts of students making these migrations.</p> <h2>How should I interpret this chart?</h2> <p>Major migration patterns can vary greatly from major to major, and from department to department. Consider looking at migration patterns of other similar and distinct majors, and asking yourself&hellip;</p> <ul> <li>How does my major compare to others with respect to the number of students declared at entry?</li> <li>For student who migrate in, do we tend draw students in from a wide variety of other majors or from just a few? Do they tend to come from closely related majors or from far afield? What impact might this have on their progress towards degree in my major?</li> <li>For student who migrate out, do we tend lose students to a wide variety of other majors or to just a few? Do they tend to move into closely related majors or to majors that are far afield? If they move to majors that are far afield, has their time spent in our major served them well or set them back with regards to their progress towards degree?</li> </ul>', 'chris', '2016-09-21 17:00:12', '2016-09-21 17:00:12', NULL),
(172, 2, 'sankey/chart', 'Published', 'sankey/chart', 1, 1, '<p id="migration_chart_labels"><span>Major at Entry</span> <span>Graduation Major</span></p><figure id="migrations_chart"></figure>', 'creeser', '2016-09-19 22:00:24', '2016-09-22 18:14:06', NULL),
(91, 2, 'bublin/explanations', 'Draft description...', 'bublin/explanations', 1, 2, '<h1>CSU/National Peers Chart Explanations (Draft)</h1> <h2>What is the purpose of this chart?</h2> <p>The inclination to make comparisons between campuses is natural, but as an activity it is fraught with the potential for misinterpretation. Campuses differ in many ways that can render comparisons of student outcomes such as graduation rates moot. Differences in student body size, rural/urban setting, population characteristics including academic preparation at entry, along with many other factors, may significantly affect outcomes regardless of academic practices or policies employed at the campus. However, most CSU campuses can point to one or a few other campuses that they regard as their closest peers. When selected carefully, observations of CSU peer changes in outcomes such as graduation rates and achievement gaps may help identify peer campuses that are having greater success, or, if peer campuses see the same changes over time, may help identify changes that are the result of influences external to campus practices or policies.</p> <h2>What data am I looking at?</h2> <p>The data used to create these charts were taken from data originally sent by each campus&apos; Institutional Research department to the Chancellor&apos;s Office in order to meet the campus&apos; Federal and State data reporting requirements. This page tracks selected student outcome (Graduation Rates, Achievement Gaps) and enrollment measures (Pell recipients) for all of the CSU campuses.</p> <h2>How do I interact with this page?</h2> <p>Both Charts</p> <ul> <li>Use the drop-down menu at the top of the page to choose to view data for 4-year or 6-year First-Time Full-Time Freshmen or 2-year or 4 year Transfer students.</li> <li>The campus to which you are primarily affiliated should be selected by default. To select or deselect any campus, click on its name in the figure legend.</li> <li>Hover over any data point to see the institution&apos;s specific values for an individual year.</li> </ul> <p>CSU Comparisons chart:</p> <p>This chart provides an animated view of changes in Achievement Gaps and Graduation rates over time.</p> <ul> <li>Click the play button to see changes in motion for the selected student group. Click on the timeline tool if you want to see these values for a particular year.</li> </ul> <p>Historical Trends line chart:</p> <p>This chart provides static views of individual measures (Graduation rates, Achievement Gaps, Pell recipient enrollment, etc.) over time.</p> <ul> <li>Use the drop-down menu at the top of the chart space to select a specific measure.</li> </ul>', 'creeser', '2016-09-13 18:01:08', '2016-09-13 18:01:08', NULL),
