e equivalent undergraduate</td> <td>68 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Status as a commuter campus</td> <td>67 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Average high school GPA among college freshmen</td> <td>64 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Percent of undergraduate students age 25 and over</td> <td>62 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Admissions selectivity, per <em>Barron&apos;s Profiles of American Colleges</em></td> <td>54 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Percent of undergraduates who are enrolled part-time</td> <td>51 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Percent of degrees awarded in Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics</td> <td>30 points</td> </tr> <tr> <td>Historically Black College or University</td> <td>27 points</td> </tr> </tbody> </table> <h2>Average Annual Change</h2> <p>The average annual improvement rates reported in the table to the right of the Historical Trends line chart, were calculated using the formula below:</p> <p class="formula"><span class="numerator">G<sub>2</sub> &mdash; G<sub>1</sub></span><span class="division_line">⎯⎯⎯⎯⎯⎯⎯</span><span class="denominator">Y<sub>2</sub> &mdash; Y<sub>1</sub> </span></p> <p>where <em>G</em><sub>2</sub> is the most recent year&apos;s graduation rate, <em>G</em><sub>1</sub> is the graduation rate of the earliest year in the selected time frame, <em>Y</em><sub>2</sub> is the most recent year, and <em>Y</em><sub>1</sub> is the earliest year in the selected time frame.</p> <h2>Projected Trends</h2> <p>Two methodologies are presented for projecting graduation rates for CSU campuses: "Peer Benchmarking Methodology" and "Linear Model".</p> <h3>Peer Benchmarking Methodology</h3> <p>This methodology calculates a central projection along with related upper and lower bounds. The central projection is generated by first calculating the average 2008 graduation rate for the selected campus&apos; top five peers. This value is presented as the 2008 value for the three "Peer Benchmarking Methodology" projections. (Note that the "top five peers" can include the campus itself if it is among the top five performing institutions among its CRO peers.) For the central projection, subsequent values incrementally increase (or decrease) the 2008 value by cumulatively adding the average rate of change observed over the past 5 years for the top five peer institutions. Upper and lower projections are also based on the 2008 average graduation rate for the top five peers. These values are incremented by cumulatively adding the average rate of change observed over the past 5 years for the top five peer institutions plus the standard deviation of this average change (for the upper bound) or minus the standard deviation of this average change (for the lower bound).</p> <h3>Linear Model (Linear Programming Model)</h3> <p>The linear programming (or linear optimization model) generates potential campus graduation rate targets by working backwards from specific pre-determined constraints. This includes specific System-wide graduation rate targets (35% or 40% for 4-year graduation rate goals, and 65% or 70% for 6-year graduation rate goals), as well as closing URM and Pell achievement gaps at every campus. It provides an alternate approach for goal-setting compared to trend and/or benchmarking approaches. Campus graduation rates are broken down by Pell and URM status, resulting in 92 different graduation rate groups that comprise the whole System (23 campuses X URM/Non-URM groups X Pell Eligible/Non-Eligible groups).</p> <p>Campus rates are derived based on optimizing an objective function by varying graduation rates across the groups that minimizes the variance in the percentage point change in graduation rates across all groups. Using this as the objective, all groups should improve by similar rates. This will necessarily diverge with the additional constraints of meeting all of the Graduation Initiative objectives, including closing achievement gaps. Rates are based on the latest cohort for which final Pell grant awards are available,