(157, 2, 'sankey/explanations', 'Draft description...', 'sankey/explanations', 1, 2, '<h1>Chart Explanation</h1> <h2>What data am I looking at?</h2> <p>The data used to create this chart were&nbsp;taken from data originally sent by each campus&apos; Institutional Research department to the Chancellor&apos;s Office in order to meet the campus&apos; Federal and State data reporting requirements. The Major Migration chart shows the relative proportion of students migrating into or out of the selected major (or remaining within the selected major). This chart is based only on the major as declared at entry and at graduation for students who began at the selected campus as first-time full-time freshmen. It does not show intervening major changes for students who made multiple migrations during their academic career. This chart also does not include students who are still enrolled, who transferred out of the university, or who did not graduate.</p> <h2>How do I interact with this page?</h2> <p>Use the menus at the top to select a campus, college, and major. Use the radio buttons at the top right to select different perspectives. You can choose to view just migrations into the selected major (the default view), migrations out of the selected major, or both at the same time. You can hover over a specific path to see the percent of student migrating from or to a specific major. You can also select the Data Tables tab to see the actual counts of students making these migrations.</p> <h2>How should I interpret this chart?</h2> <p>Major migration patterns can vary greatly from major to major, and from department to department. Consider looking at migration patterns of other similar and distinct majors, and asking yourself&hellip;</p> <ul> <li>How does my major compare to others with respect to the number of students declared at entry?</li> <li>For student who migrate in, do we tend draw students in from a wide variety of other majors or from just a few? Do they tend to come from closely related majors or from far afield? What impact might this have on their progress towards degree in my major?</li> <li>For student who migrate out, do we tend lose students to a wide variety of other majors or to just a few? Do they tend to move into closely related majors or to majors that are far afield? If they move to majors that are far afield, has their time spent in our major served them well or set them back with regards to their progress towards degree?</li> </ul>', 'chris', '2016-09-19 23:12:36', '2016-09-19 23:12:36', NULL);

